                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d368">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.00 Revolutions/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bliss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-09-13T15:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 13, 1930—3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>101. The Department desires to obtain promptly any reliable information with
                    respect to the control exercised by the Provisional Government over the
                    provinces, particularly those parts of Argentina where the party of President
                    Irigoyen has been successful, e. g., the Province of Buenos Aires.</p>
                <p>Also the Department desires to be kept informed with respect to the relations of
                    the Provisional Government, which is understood to be made up largely of members
                    of the Conservative Party and other political elements.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
